Simple VaR Forecast by GARCH(1,1)

Felix Chan

2/12/2018

VaR Forecast

  • Forecast a worst case scenario for financial retunr.
  • The distirbution of financial return is time varying.

Bitcoin

  • We are going to use the return of bitcoin/USD exchange rate as example.
  • Data downloaded from Quandl.com
m <- read.csv("BITSTAMP-USD.csv", header = TRUE, colClasses = c('Date', 'numeric', 'numeric', 'numeric','numeric','numeric','numeric','numeric'))
dm <- read.csv("BITSTAMP-USD_delta.csv", header = TRUE, colClasses = c('Date', 'numeric', 'numeric', 'numeric','numeric','numeric','numeric','numeric'))

Let’s have a look at the data

priceplot <- ggplot(m)+geom_line(aes(Date, Last))
returnplot <- ggplot(dm)+geom_line(aes(Date, Last))
grid.arrange(priceplot, returnplot, ncol=2)

GARCH(1,1)

  • GARCH(1,1): long history from Engle’s ARCH (1982) and Bollerslev’s GARCH (1986) \[ \begin{align} y_t =& c + e_t \\ e_t =& \eta_t \sqrt{h_t} \qquad \eta_t \sim D(0,1) \\ h_t =& \omega + \alpha e^2_{t-1} + \beta h_{t-1} \end{align} \]

Estimation

  • Estimating the parameters, \(c\), \(\omega\), \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) can be done by the packge rugarch

Estimation

  • first we need to define the number of out-of-sample forecasts and the specification of the model.
N <- 300
rspec <- ugarchspec(variance.model = list(model="sGARCH", garchOrder=c(1,1)), mean.model=list(armaOrder=c(1,0), include.mean=TRUE))

Estimation

  • Generally use Maximum Likelihood with a normal density.
M <- dim(dm)[1]
rfit <- ugarchfit(data=dm$Last, spec=rspec, out.sample = N)
rforecast <- ugarchforecast(rfit, n.ahead = 1, n.roll = N-1)
overallfit <- rbind(as.matrix(rfit@fit$sigma, c((M-N),1)), t(rforecast@forecast$sigmaFor))
rfit

Constructing VaR

p <- 0.01
dm1f <- cbind(dm,overallfit)
colnames(dm1f)[9] <- "hfit"
var <- qdist(distribution = "norm", p)*overallfit
temp <- rep(0,M)
temp[(M-N+1):M] <- 1
dm1f <- cbind(dm1f, var, as.factor(temp))
colnames(dm1f)[10] <- "var"
colnames(dm1f)[11] <- 'outsample'
ggplot(dm1f)+ ylab("Bitcoin Return") + geom_line(aes(Date, Last)) + geom_line(aes(Date, var, color=outsample)) + scale_color_manual(values = c("blue", "red"))
